      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Sense of Humor</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Kelley Dupuis letter agrees with Michael Beckerman's May 28 article on Saul Bellow's ironic sense of humor; notes note on CD box stating that music was played 'on original instruments' (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I read Michael Beckerman's article regarding Saul Bellow's ''gaffes'' on the subject of music [''Ravelstein Knows Everything, Almost,'' May 28] with amusement, as, I imagine, Mr. Bellow might have too. I've always felt that his ironic sense of humor was one of Mr. Bellow's most endearing attributes as a writer.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I read Michael Beckerman's article regarding Saul Bellow's ''gaffes'' on the subject of music [''Ravelstein Knows Everything, Almost,'' May 28] with amusement, as, I imagine, Mr. Bellow might have too. I've always felt that his ironic sense of humor was one of Mr. Bellow's most endearing attributes as a writer.</p>
        <p>Later, after I'd finished reading the paper and cleaning my apartment, I sat down to listen to some Palestrina. I enjoyed ''Christmas Mass and Three Christmas Motets'' in an Archiv recording by the Gabrieli Consort and Players. While enjoying this CD, I reached over and read the notes on the box. Right there on the back, at the bottom, are the words, ''On original instruments.''</p>
        <p>KELLEY DUPUIS  Baltimore</p>
        <p>BELLOW AND MUSIC</p>
      </block>
